[1] Norovirus, students - USA (Pennsylvania): not confirmed
Date: Sat 27 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PittsburghLIVE.com, Sat 27 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/tribune-review/trib/pittsburgh/s_186619.html>


USA: norovirus not confirmed as cause of Cornell School District outbreak
-----------------------------------------------
Laboratory tests failed to confirm norovirus as the culprit in an illness
outbreak at the Cornell School District [see: Viral gastroenteritis update
2004 (11) 20040325.0833], a health official said on Fri 26 Mar 2004. The
state Health Department tested specimens from 8 people sickened by the
outbreak at the Coraopolis school looking for norovirus, but didn't find
it, Allegheny County Health Department spokesman Guillermo Cole said.

"This does not definitively rule out norovirus. Sometimes it can be
difficult to isolate this virus. It just may not have been in the specimens
that we received," Cole said. "This doesn't change our thinking. We still
strongly believe this outbreak was due to some type of viral infection, and
it could still be a norovirus." Cole said more tests looking for norovirus
and other viruses will take a week to complete. The county Health
Department ruled out bacteria as a cause.

According to the latest figures, 168 people have been affected in the
outbreak, including 126 students, 13 staff members, and 29 of their
relatives. Among students, 90 per cent were of elementary school age. No
new cases have been reported since Tue 23 Mar 2004, when students were
dismissed early and the district shut down, Cole said. "That's evidence the
outbreak is subsiding," he said.

Because a virus is still the suspected cause, Cole said the effort to
disinfect the school building, which houses all of the district's students,
has not been wasted. Superintendent DJ Johnson said the district has hired
a firm to test the building to ensure that no viruses remain after the
cleaning, which started on Thu 25 Mar, is completed. The testing will add
to the cost of decontaminating the school.

[byline: Brian C Rittmeyer]

[Information on the final diagnosis would be welcomed. - Mod.CP]

