[2] Norovirus, hospital - Ireland (Cork)
Date: Wed 7 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Southern Health Board, Wed 6 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.shb.ie/class2041727922.cfm>


Ireland: norovirus outbreak at orthopedic hospital in Cork
----------------------------------------------------------
Visitors were urged to avoid Cork's Orthopedic Hospital on the night of Tue
6 Mar 2004 after the Southern Health Board (SHB) confirmed that it had been
affected by an outbreak of the winter vomiting bug [norovirus infection].
One case of [norovirus infection] has been confirmed at St Mary's
Orthopaedic Hospital in Gurranabraher.

The SHB said it was taking steps to try to prevent the outbreak from
spreading. Visitors to St Mary's are now being limited to direct relatives
of patients only. The SHB has also urged anyone who has been affected by
vomiting or acute diarrhea not to visit the hospital for at least 72 hours
after their last symptoms.

Dr Bartley Cryan, a consultant microbiologist with the SHB, warned that
only strict measures will help contain what is a highly infectious
organism. "Winter vomiting disease is highly infectious, and we are
appealing to people to stay away from the hospital," he said.

