[3] Norovirus, assisted-living center - USA (Florida): suspected
Date: Wed 7 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun Sentinel online, Wed 7 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl>


Florida: norovirus infection suspected in assisted-living center
----------------------------------------------------------------
Local health officials are investigating an outbreak of viral
gastroenteritis in a Tamarac assisted-living center that sent 16 elderly
residents to the hospital and infected 5 employees. While still waiting for
test results, investigators with the Broward County Health Department
suspect Merrill Gardens, 7650 N University Drive, was affected by a
norovirus outbreak.

Symptoms, which usually run their course in 24 to 48 hours, include
vomiting, nausea, and diarrhea. "Everything else we tested for came back
negative, so we think this is [a norovirus outbreak]," said Karen LaFleur,
the department's environmental health program consultant. Highly
contagious, norovirus infection is known to spread rapidly in places where
people are living closely together, and there have been outbreaks in South
Florida retirement homes before, LaFleur said.

The 1st Merrill Gardens case was detected 1 Apr 2004, and several other
senior citizens soon were sick. General manager Sid Rosenblatt, who also
contracted the virus, said the infected were sent to University Hospital
and Medical Center in Tamarac in order to contain the outbreak. Uninfected
residents were asked to remain in their rooms until the center, which
houses 88 elders, could be inspected and sanitized. Rosenblatt said Merrill
Gardens resumed normal operations on Tue 6 Apr and that most of those
admitted to hospital were back home.

Merrill Gardens' infection rate was low, LaFleur said, possibly because
afflicted residents were isolated early. A 50 per cent infection rate is
common. Health officials don't know how the outbreak began. Merrill
Garden's kitchen has been cleared by investigators, Rosenblatt said. The
virus can come from improperly stored or prepared food. But Tim O'Connor,
spokesman for the Palm Beach County Health Department, said the outbreaks
in his region's assisted-living centers and nursing homes typically are
brought in from the outside.

